Dialog.text: This is so weird.
Hmph. Not like this.
I have your connectome. I'm headed there now to inject your piloting skills into my skull.
Dialog.notes: [Angela Wagner] Emphasis on YOUR and MY.

Dialog.text: Yeah, like what?
Actually - you'll be obsolete 'cause I'll be able to fix them and fly them.
Dialog.notes: [Angela Wagner] Coming around. Teasing him now. Emphasis on AND.

Dialog.text: This mimic you brought me - something is definitely wrong with it. It keeps throwing various... shoes at me.

I'm serious. It's like it's punching holes to somewhere - a universe of shoes - I don't know. But, my point is, someone with sufficient Typhon abilities and a strong attachment to someplace else, like-
Yes. Exactly. Then, I think you could open a door. Maybe even walk through it.
I think I could tweak the containment shield to stabilize the mimic.
Well? What are you waiting for? I'll be in the lab.
You were right.
Three more surveillance kits missing.
Two more surveillance kits missing.
One more surveillance kit missing.
Four more surveillance kits missing.
No, that's it.
No. Nothing in the security computer. No logins used, no keycodes entered.
There's something else.
Shuttle came in last night. It's... a letter from the AIL.
If you... uhm... let me know if you need anything. Okay?
Dialog.notes: [Casey Fletcher] She knows it's probably bad news about his son.

Dialog.text: No. First time. Am I that obvious?
Is there any risk of an outbreak.
But what about the voltaic kind? Wouldn't an EMP disrupt the-
It's just... a little surreal. You know? Being here on the moon. Under a dome. Aliens. People with... psychic abilities.
That is literally what I just said.
Dialog.notes: [Terri Brown] Taken aback, like, are you mental?
